    <name>
				<text>37.2.2.1 Dice roll and binomial distribution</text>
		</name>
    <questiontext format="moodle_auto_format">
				<text><![CDATA[<p class="HELM_exercise">Exercise</p><p></p><p>A \({@sides@}\)-faced die is thrown repeatedly {@n_times@} times in all. Find:<br></p><p>\(\text{E}(X)=\) [[input:ans1]] [[validation:ans1]]&nbsp;[[feedback:prt1]]</p><p>\(V(X)= \)&nbsp;[[input:ans2]] [[validation:ans2]]&nbsp;[[feedback:prt2]]<br></p><p>where \(X\) is the random variable for the number of threes obtained.<br></p><p><b>Note:</b> Please write your answer up to 2 decimal places, if required.</p>]]></text>
		</questiontext>
    <generalfeedback format="moodle_auto_format">
				<text><![CDATA[<p>Consider the occurrence of a three, with <span class="math inline">\(X\)</span> being the number of threes thrown in {@n_times@} trials.</p>
<p>The random variable <span class="math inline">\(X\)</span> follows a binomial distribution. (Why? Refer to the beginning of this section for the criteria if necessary). A trial is the operation of throwing a die. A success is the occurrence of a 3 on a particular trial, so <span class="math inline">\(p={@prob@}\)</span>. We have <span class="math inline">\(X\sim\text{Binomial}(n={@n_times@},\ p={@prob@})\)</span> so that&nbsp;</p><p><span class="math inline">\[\text{E}(X)=np={@n_times@}\times {@prob@}= {@EX@} = {@displaydp(float(ta_1),2)@} ~(\text{to 2 d.p.})\]</span></p><p><span class="math inline">and&nbsp;</span></p><p><span class="math inline">\[\text{V}(X)=npq={@n_times@}\times {@prob@}\times (1-{@prob@})={@VX@}={@displaydp(float(ta_2),2)@} ~ (\text{to 2 d.p.}).\]</span></p>
<p>Hence the standard deviation is <span class="math inline">\(\sigma(X)=\sqrt{{@VX@}} = {@displaydp(float(sqrt(VX)),2)@}\) to 2 d.p.</span></p>
<p><span class="math inline">\(\text{E}(X)={@ta_1@}\)</span> implies that in {@n_times@} throws of a fair {@sides@}-faced die we would expect, on average, to see {@ta_1@} threes. This makes perfect sense, of course.</p>]]></text>
		</generalfeedback>
